# Natural numbers: definition

Axiom.  There exists a type ‚Ñï (the natural numbers) with an element 0 ‚àà ‚Ñï and a function s : ‚Ñï ‚Üí ‚Ñï such that

  a. There is no n ‚àà ‚Ñï such that s(n) = 0.  [succ 0]
  b. For all n, m ‚àà ‚Ñï, if s(n) = s(m) then n = m.  [succ injective]
  c. Let P : ‚Ñï ‚Üí ùîπ.  If 0 ‚àà P, and k ‚àà P implies s(k) ‚àà P for all k ‚àà ‚Ñï, then P = ‚Ñï.  [induction]

Lemma.  Let x ‚àà ‚Ñï.  Suppose that x ‚â† 0.  Then there is some y ‚àà ‚Ñï such that x = s(y).

Proof.  Let

    B = { x : ‚Ñï | if x ‚â† 0 then there is some y : ‚Ñï such that x = s(y) }.

We must show that B = ‚Ñï.  First, it is obvious that 0 ‚àà B.  Assume x ‚àà B.  Then there exists y : ‚Ñï such that s(x) = s(y).  Thus s(x) ‚àà B.  We have shown that for all x : ‚Ñï, x ‚àà B implies s(x) ‚àà B.  Therefore by [induction] B = ‚Ñï.

# Natural numbers: addition

Axiom.  There is a binary operation + : ‚Ñï ‚Üí ‚Ñï ‚Üí ‚Ñï such that for all x, y ‚àà ‚Ñï,

  a. x + 0 = x.                    [add 0]
  b. x + s(y) = s(x + y).     [add succ]

Lemma.  For all x, y ‚àà ‚Ñï, x + (y + 0) = (x + y) + 0.  [assoc 0]

Theorem (associativity of addition).  For all x, y, z ‚àà ‚Ñï,

    x + (y + z) = (x + y) + z.

Proof.  Let x, y : ‚Ñï.  Let

    A = { z : ‚Ñï | x + (y + z) = (x + y) + z }.

We must show that A = ‚Ñï.  First, 0 ‚àà A by [assoc 0].  Second, let z ‚àà A.  Then x + (y + z) = (x + y) + z.  Now

    x + (y + s(z)) = x + s(y + z)    by [add succ]
                          = s(x + (y + z))  by [add succ]
                          = s((x + y) + z)  by the inductive hypothesis
                          = (x + y) + s(z)  by [add succ].

Thus s(z) ‚àà A.  We have shown that for all z : ‚Ñï, z ‚àà A implies s(z) ‚àà A.  Hence A = ‚Ñï by [nat induction].

Lemma.

    a. For all x ‚àà ‚Ñï, 0 + x = x.                    [comm lemma a]
    b. For all x, y ‚àà ‚Ñï, s(x) + y = s(x + y).  [comm lemma b]

Proof.

    a. Let A = { x : ‚Ñï | 0 + x = x }.  Then 0 ‚àà A by [add 0].  Suppose that x ‚àà A.  Then

        0 + s(x) = s(0 + x)     by [add succ]
                      = s(x)           by the inductive hypothesis.

    Hence s(x) ‚àà A.  So A = ‚Ñï.

    b. Let x : ‚Ñï.  Let B = { y : ‚Ñï | s(x) + y = s(x + y) }.  Then 0 ‚àà B by [add 0].  Suppose that y ‚àà B.  Then

        s(x) + s(y) = s(s(x) + y)   by [add succ]
                          = s(s(x + y))   by the inductive hypothesis
                          = s(x + s(y))   by [add succ].

    This shows that s(y) ‚àà B.  Hence B = ‚Ñï.

Theorem (commutativity of addition).  For all x, y : ‚Ñï,

    x + y = y + x.

Proof.  Let y : ‚Ñï.  Let C = { x ‚àà ‚Ñï | x + y = y + x }.  By [comm lemma a] 0 + y = y = y + 0, whence 0 ‚àà C.  Suppose that x ‚àà C.  Then

    s(x) + y = s(x + y)     by [comm lemma b]
                  = s(y + x)     by the inductive hypothesis
                  = y + s(x)     by [add succ].

So s(x) ‚àà C.  Hence C = ‚Ñï.

Theorem (cancellation law for addition).  For all x, y, z ‚àà ‚Ñï,

    x + z = y + z implies x = y.

Proof.  Consider any x, y : ‚Ñï.  Let A = { z : ‚Ñï | x + z = y + z implies x = y }.  We must prove that A = ‚Ñï.  First, 0 ‚àà A by [add 0].  Second, assume that z ‚àà A.  Then z ‚àà { z : ‚Ñï | x + z = y + z implies x = y }.  Assume that x + s(z) = y + s(z).  Then by [add succ] s(x + z) = s(y + z).  Therefore by [succ injective] x + z = y + z.  Hence by inductive hypothesis x = y.  We have shown that x + s(z) = y + s(z) implies x = y, that is s(z) ‚àà A.  Therefore for all z: ‚Ñï, z ‚àà A implies s(z) ‚àà A.  By [induction] A = ‚Ñï.

